ver01/data/sn96027724/00271761648/1908030101/0445.xml", "segments": [{"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn96027724/1908-03-01/ed-1/?sp=6"], "batch": ["fu_bathouse_ver01"], "campaigns": [], "composite_location": ["0/united states/", "1/united states/florida/", "2/united states/florida/duval/", "3/united states/florida/duval/jacksonville/", "2/united states/florida/volusia/", "3/united states/florida/volusia/de land/"], "contributor": ["university of florida"], "date": "1908-03-01", "dates": ["1908-03-01"], "description": ["6 OUR CUBAN NEIGHBORS A Review of the Fruit and and Vegetable Condition in Cuba by our Regular Correspondent Cuban vegetables were shipped to New York exceptionally ealy this season the first supplies arriving in November Tomatoes and peppers formed the bulk of them the latter at first bringing good prices The excellent prospects which growers and commission men saw before them soon faded away with the financial panic and a superabundance of stock No less than twentyfive thousand cases were shipped during December and the prices which had been as high as from 300 to 350 dropped before Christmas to from SIOO to 150 and stand now at 75 cents The general result of the tomato season then has been disappointing to the growers It was certainly a record crop for Cuba and has brought a record bad price The reasons for this are three In many cases the tomatoes are picked from nine to ten days before they are put on the market and as a result when they arrive hey are either still green or over ripe The amount of green stuff which has ac cumulated in New York and other markets this year is beyond concep"], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-01-27T16:57:42.656Z", "group": ["ndnp/fu", "university-of-florida-awardee"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn96027724/1908-03-01/ed-1/?sp=6", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:fu:batch_fu_bathouse_ver01:data:sn96027724:0